\layout Subsection

Force Field Box
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Force-Field-Box}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard
\added_space_bottom smallskip \noindent \align left 

\series bold 
\emph on 
Box Keyword
\series default 
\emph default 
: 
\family typewriter 
.<Force_Field>
\layout Standard

This box contains all the ncessary information necessary to specify the
 force field for the tip-surface interaction.
 The force field consists of three components: the van der Waals force,
 chemical short-range and long-range forces.
 
\layout Standard

Presently, the vdW force is given within the plane-sphere model, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F_{vdW}(z)=-\frac{HR}{6z^{2}}\label{eq:vdw}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset 

 is the Hamaker's constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset 

 - the sphere radius, 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset 

 - distance of the sphere bottom from the surface plane.
 
\layout Standard

The long-range chemical component of the force, which works above some critical
 vertical height 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{bound}$
\end_inset 

, is generally given by the expression: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F_{lr}(z)=\sum_{n=0}^{6}\frac{g_{n}}{(z+z_{0})^{n}},\,\,\,\,\, z\geq z_{bound}\label{eq:long_range_force}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{n}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{0}$
\end_inset 

are fitting parameters.
 
\layout Standard

The short-range part of the chemical force is specified in a file on a lateral
 grid with respect to the direct lattice vectors of the surface, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{1}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{2}$
\end_inset 

.
 At each grid point the force is specified for a number of 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{z}$
\end_inset 

 (not necessarily equidistant) 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset 

 values below 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{bound}$
\end_inset 

.
 If the grid points along 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{1}$
\end_inset 

 are numbered by 
\begin_inset Formula $0,1,\ldots,N_{1}$
\end_inset 

 and similarly for the points along the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}_{2}$
\end_inset 

 direction, numbered as 
\begin_inset Formula $0,1,\ldots,N_{2}$
\end_inset 

, then the force is provided for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula $(i=0,\ldots,N_{1}\,\textrm{and}\, j=0,\ldots,N_{2})$
\end_inset 

.
 To preserve periodicity of the lattice, the force fields for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i=N_{1}$
\end_inset 

 (any 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

) should be identical; similarly for values of 
\begin_inset Formula $j=0$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j=N_{2}$
\end_inset 

 (any 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset 

).
 The format of the force field file is described in section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Structure-of-the-force-file}

\end_inset 

 below.
 
\layout Standard

