\layout Subsubsection

Doing a 2D scan
\layout Standard

Using elementary stages as described above one can program in any particular
 movement of the cantilever across the surface including doing a 2D scan.
 This last option may be tedious though since many times the same pattern
 of line scans should be repeated.
 To avoid this, the 2D scan can be automated using another sub-box structure
 inside the 
\family typewriter 
<Elementary_Stages> 
\family default 
box.
 
\layout Standard

The basic idea is that a 2D scan can be simulated by repeating e.g.
 4 elementary stages: 
\layout Enumerate

a line scan along direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset 

 during a long time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset 


\layout Enumerate

a line scan along the perpendicular direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset 

 during a very short time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}$
\end_inset 


\layout Enumerate

a line scan along direction 
\begin_inset Formula $-\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset 

 during time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset 


\layout Enumerate

a line scan along the perpendicular direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset 

 during a very short time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}$
\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Some other possibilities for a 2D scan also exist, e.g.
 by repeating only 3 stages:
\layout Enumerate

a line scan along direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset 

 during a long time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset 


\layout Enumerate

a line scan along direction 
\begin_inset Formula $-\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset 

 during the same time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset 


\layout Enumerate

a line scan along the perpendicular direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset 

 during a very short time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}$
\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Thus any scan can be viewed as an identical sequence of structures, each
 consisting of several elementary stages.
 The number of sequences determines the length of the scan in the direction
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset 

, whereas the length of the scan in the perpendicular direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset 

 is determined by the time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset 

 in the examples above.
 
\layout Standard

It is possible to position the scan sub-box arbitrarily between any stage
 sub-boxes inside the 
\family typewriter 
<Elementary_Stages> 
\family default 
box as shown in the example in section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Example-Input-File}

\end_inset 

.
 Therefore, it is possible to do some number of elementary stages, then
 a scan, then some other elementary stages, another scan, etc.
 The total length of this chain of stages is only limited by the maximum
 number of stages and scans allowed as given by the two parameters in the
 
\family typewriter 
virtual_param.inc
\family default 
 file (see section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:virtual_param.inc-file}

\end_inset 

).
 Note that every scan is eventually constructed as a set of stages, so that
 the parameter 
\family typewriter 
N_of_stages_max
\family default 
 can easily become too small and need to be increased, and the code recompiled.
 
\layout Standard

To start a scan, place the keyword 
\layout Standard
\added_space_top smallskip \added_space_bottom smallskip \noindent \align left 

\family typewriter 
==={begin_scan}===
\layout Standard
\noindent \align left 
after a stage sub-box
\begin_inset Foot
collapsed false

\layout Standard

Note that you have to do the approach anyway, so that the stage sub-box
 should always precede any of the scan boxes.
\end_inset 

.
 The next line 
\emph on 
should
\emph default 
 contain the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

keyword + parameter
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 structure: 
\layout Subsubsection*
\noindent 
No_of_sequences
\layout Standard
\align left 

\emph on 
Parameters
\emph default 
: number of sequences
\layout Standard
\align left 

\emph on 
Default
\emph default 
: none
\layout Standard
\added_space_bottom smallskip \noindent \align left 

\emph on 
Example
\emph default 
: 
\family typewriter 
\size footnotesize 
No_of_sequences 100
\layout Standard
\noindent \align left 
This parameter defines the number of times each sequence is to be repeated.
 After that, the elementary sequence, consisiting of elementary passages
 (i.e.
 stages) follows in the same way as described in section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Specifying-each-elementary}

\end_inset 

.
 The scan sub-box is terminated with the keyword
\layout Standard
\added_space_top smallskip \added_space_bottom smallskip \noindent \align left 

\family typewriter 
==={end_scan}===
\layout Standard
\added_space_bottom smallskip \noindent \align left 
